  "infoTitle": "Information",
  "infoSectionWhatIs": "What is N-back?",
  "infoSectionWhatIsBody": "N-back is a working-memory task. A stream of stimuli appears one at a time; for each one you decide whether it matches the stimulus shown N steps earlier. Single N-back uses one channel (e.g. position), dual N-back uses two independent channels (typically position + audio), and quad N-back uses four. Each channel is judged independently — a match on position doesn't imply a match on audio.",
  "infoSectionJaeggi": "The Jaeggi study",
  "infoSectionJaeggiBody": "Jaeggi et al. (2008) showed that ~19 days of dual N-back training transferred to gains in fluid intelligence (Gf), measured by Raven-style progressive matrices. The adaptive protocol they used drives this app's defaults: 20 scoring trials per session, 500 ms stimulus, 2500 ms ISI, 30% match probability, and adaptive N — increase when per-channel accuracy ≥ 80%, decrease when below 50%.",
  "infoSectionMetrics": "Score metrics",
  "infoMetricHits": "Hits — you pressed Match on a trial where the stimulus really did match the one N steps ago.",
  "infoMetricMisses": "Misses — there was a real match, but you didn't press.",
  "infoMetricFalseAlarms": "False + (false alarms) — you pressed Match, but there was no real match.",
  "infoMetricCorrectRejections": "Correct − (correct rejections) — there was no match and you correctly didn't press.",
  "infoMetricAccuracy": "Accuracy = hits / (hits + misses + false alarms). Penalises both missed matches and wrong presses.",
  "infoMetricDPrime": "d′ (d-prime) — sensitivity index from signal-detection theory: z(hit rate) − z(false-alarm rate). Higher means you separate signal from noise better, independent of any tendency to press too often or too rarely.",
  "infoSectionTips": "Practice tips",
  "infoSectionTipsBody": "• Train daily — short, focused sessions beat sporadic long ones.\n• Don't try to verbalise the sequence; let it sit in working memory.\n• Plateaus are normal — d′ keeps improving even after accuracy stalls.\n• Switch off the Jaeggi adaptive mode if you want to train at a fixed N.",

